John Edward: Language skills are fundamental to the citizens of the world
The independent educational centres of Scotland have a history of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in the examinations that are reinforced by the individual and collective successes collected in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent colleges are designed to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language that he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, he reaches his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that if we want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's reviews, we can see that languages are at the highest level of the classification tables, being the highest approved rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students studying foreign languages received an A, the highest grade.
The data collected from the 74 SCIS centres showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that the independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages by considering them a fundamental competency that both children and young people will need in the future without a doubt.
Currently, as a subject, languages are considered to be at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Employment and Skills Commission revealed that, of the reasons given by entrepreneurs for the difficulties in filling jobs, 17% were attributed to the shortage of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last forever.
The ability to communicate directly with persons from foreign countries will enable that person to automatically advance to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to keep a conversation. Moreover, it was established that the only language spoken by a percentage of two digits, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If you know a number of languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find a quality job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools, you can always choose between several languages provided by teaching staff specialized in this field.
The independent educational centres in Scotland devote all their efforts to provide a learning environment that prepares children and that teams with the necessary skills to succeed, whatever lies ahead for them.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "competences for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do this.
