Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
Thanks to a new course this year at Harvard University, all university students sleep more in an attempt to fight against the growing machist culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found out that students at the number one university in the world often have no idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, sleep medicine professor at Harvard School of Medicine, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, it is believed that his first class in the United States.
His motivation to start the course arose after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl approached me and asked why she just learned about this now, in her last year.
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," The Telegraph commented.
The course, given for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and executive director of health services at the university, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students barely slept during the week.
The one hour course of duration includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of the lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed of how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of infarction, embolism, depression and cancer.
Afterwards, an icon of campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know you're not going to change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco," said Professor Czeisler.
He said that the culture of pride for "to spend the night sailing" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure that students are subjected to meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping enough time and a good quality dream should be the "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He pointed out that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to extend it to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler's recommendation is that students consider putting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emit the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter circadian rhythms, so they would end up having problems to stay asleep.
