Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that culminated with the device known as Geiger counter.
Count Geiger, who since then is a pillar of science, has also become a pillar of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "The Crown bells", with actors Roy Rogers and Dale Evans on seemingly incompatible roles of cowboy scientists:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
By putting your headphones on, you can hear the effect of the waves emitted by the radioactive activity of minerals."
Evans: "It's like a radio!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, when he was about to age 63.
But the invention that bears his name is still alive.
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" malignant cells
