HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% more than new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
There are more than 820,000 people in the country, according to the health authorities.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, some 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of these were sexually infected, which implies a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV was rapidly spread by some parts of China as a result of an infected blood transfusion.
However, the number of people who contracted HIV in this way has been reduced in practice entirely, declared the Chinese health authorities at a congress held in Yunnan province.
Every year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increases by about 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is a serious problem in the LGTB community in China.
Homosexuality was desecrated in China in 1997, but the LGTB collective suffers from much discrimination.
Due to the conservative values of the country, studies have estimated that between 70% and 90% of men who have sex with other men will end up marrying women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are not to use adequate protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to drugs against HIV as part of an attempt to deal with the problem.
