What is the "Global Citizen Festival"? Did you manage to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music festival, where an impressive star sign is gathered for an equally impressive mission: to end poverty in the world.
This year, in its seventh edition, the Global Citizen Festival will see how tens of thousands of people will move to the Great Lawn of Central Park to enjoy performances such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness of the real goal of the event: to end extreme poverty in 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international awareness group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
If you want to receive a free entry for the event (unless you can pay for a VIP entry), concert attendees have had to complete a series of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, sending emails to a world leader, making a phone call or anything else that will serve to raise awareness about their goal of ending poverty.
However, what has Global Citizen achieved at 12 years of age to achieve its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding with a free concert a genuine way to persuade people to take action or is it just a form of so-called "clectivism", which is called the posture that we adopt when we think we are doing something really useful by signing an online request or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen claims to have registered more than 19 million "actions" of its supporters in favour of a large number of diverse objectives.
Thanks to these actions, they claim that world leaders announced commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, which will affect the lives of more than 2250 million people in 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements arising from their actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that guaranteed funds have directly influenced nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Among the most important commitments is "The Power of Nutrition", an association of investors and executives based in the United Kingdom united with the common commitment to "help children grow and develop with all their potential." To this end, it has been proposed to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4700 tweets from Global Citizens' collaborators.
"Thanks to the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like you, we can mark a small milestone in the history of the social injustice of malnutrition," said Tracey Ullman, ambassador of "The Power of Nutrition", to the crowd during a concert in April 2018 in London.
The group also stated that, after more than 5000 actions were carried out to improve nutrition in the United Kingdom for mothers and children, the government announced the financing of a project, Power of Nutrition, with which 5 million women and children will benefit from nutrition-related interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on your website about what we believe can be done to remedy extreme poverty,
a collaborator from Global Citizen replied: "It will be a long and hard road and, on many occasions, we will stumble and fall.
But, as previously achieved the human rights movement and against apartheid, we will achieve our goals, because we are stronger together.
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monae are some of the events we will count on at this year's New York event, which will be presented by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
