The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state of the Scottish Highlands, attempts to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything is expected to shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the common and soprano bats, as well as the Daubenton river bats and long-eared browns of the Inverewe gardens in Western Ross.
Special tape recorders will be placed in strategic locations of the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds that are collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of bat calls and what species do.
A report and a map of the habitat will then be produced to create a detailed image of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows and how forests for bats and other associated species should be maintained.
The bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have been significantly reduced in the last century.
They are threatened by the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electric wiring may also pose a risk to them, as well as insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of construction materials or attacks of domestic cats.
The bats aren't really blind,
but because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the theme of bats very seriously.
He has ten trained experts in the field, who are dedicated to regularly conducting surveys, nest inspections and, on occasion, rescues.
The organization has inaugurated even the first and only reserve dedicated to Scotland bats in the state of Thraveve in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The director of the property, David Thompson, says it's the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Thrave, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the proper habitat.
However, there are still many unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand better what they need to develop."
It stresses the importance of checking whether there are bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, since an infant colony can be accidentally destroyed and 400 females and females could be killed, which would mean killing a whole local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said, "We still have much to learn about bats and many other species that we don't know how their populations evolve."
