Federal prosecutors exceptionally seek the death penalty for suspected terrorist attacks in New York City
Federal prosecutors in New York are looking for the death penalty for Sayfullo Saipov, the suspect of the terrorist attack in New York City that killed eight people, an exceptional punishment that has not been executed in the state for a federal crime since 1953.
Saipov, aged 30, allegedly used a Home Depot rental truck to carry out an attack on a bike lane last October on the Lower Manhattan West Side Highway, bringing down the pedestrians and cyclists on his way.
To justify a death penalty, prosecutors must prove that Saipov killed the eight victims "intendedly" and caused "intendedly" serious bodily injuries, in accordance with the notice of intent to apply for the death penalty, filed in the South New York District.
The two charges involve a possible death penalty, according to the judicial document.
Several weeks after the attack, a large federal jury presented Saipov with an indictment of 22 charges involving eight organized crime murder charges, which often use federal prosecutors in these cases, and a charge of violence and destruction of motorized vehicles.
The attack required "substantial planning and premeditation," according to prosecutors, which described the way Saipov did it as "atrocious, cruel and depraved."
"Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov caused injuries, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco", is specified in the notice of intent.
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It has been a decade since the South District of New York was prosecuting a death penalty case.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was found guilty of murdering two drug traffickers, but was finally sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The last time a death penalty was executed in a federal case in New York was to Julius and Ethel Rosenberg in 1953. This marriage was executed after they were convicted of conspiracy to commit spying for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
The two Rosenbergs were executed in the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
Saipov, an immigrant from Uzbekistan, demonstrated his lack of remorse during the days and months after the attack, according to judicial documents.
According to the police, he told the investigators he felt good about what he had done.
According to the charge, Saipov told the authorities that for his attack he was inspired by watching ISIS videos on his phone.
He also requested that the ISIS flag be removed in his hospital room, the police said.
He has been found not guilty of the indictment of 22 charges.
David Patton, one of the federal public defense lawyers representing Saipov, said they are "obviously disappointed" with the prosecutor's decision.
"We believe that the decision to seek the death penalty instead of accepting a sentence of guilt with life imprisonment without possibility of release will only prolong the trauma of these events for all the people involved," Patton said.
Saipov ' s defence team had previously asked prosecutors not to apply for the death penalty.
