Trade war between the United States and China could benefit Beijing
The first rescues of the trade war between the United States and China were deafening, and although there is still much left to finish the battle, a break between countries could benefit Beijing, experts say.
Donald Trump, President of the United States, launched the first warning early in the year by placing tariffs on major Chinese exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs affecting $200 billion (£150,000 million) in products, which carries taxes to half of the products entering the United States from China.
Beijing has, on every occasion, taken equivalent reprisals, recently applying five to ten percent tariffs to US products worth $60 billion.
China has committed itself to equalizing US attacks, and it is unlikely that the second most powerful economy in the world will soon weaken.
Getting Washington back would mean yielding to demands, but publicly submitting to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of the United States trade war could positively help China in the long term by reducing interdependence between the two economies.
"The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing can make it possible for it to begin an economic downturn in either of the two countries is actually much more dangerous than the viewers have recognized so far," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher focused on Asia issues for the strategic cabinet Center for New American Security.
Syria is ready to return refugees, says the Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria states that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has been fought for more than seven years.
In a previous speech by the United Nations General Assembly, Minister for Foreign Affairs Walid al-Moualem said that the conditions of the country were improving.
"The situation on the ground is today more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by terrorists to try to restore normality.
All the conditions for voluntary return to the country of refugees who had to abandon it have already been laid down because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people who still live in the country and need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem recognized that the Syrian regime would appreciate the help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he also stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that promoted insurgency.
