Red tide update: Decrease concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (Floro Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends approximately 130 miles from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles from Hillsborough County Coast, but in fewer places if compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and its coast, concentrations between low and high on the coast of Hillsborough County, concentrations at bottom to high in Manatee County, concentrations at bottom to high in Sarasota County and its coast, concentrations at bottom to half in Charlotte County, concentrations at bottom to high in Lee County and at its coast, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation problems have been reported in the northwest of Florida during the past week.
